Description: NanGate Library Creation Platform™ is an integrated and easy-to-use solution for the creation and optimization of digital cell libraries.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: Standard-cell libraries were introduced more than 40 years ago to help IC designers keep up with the increasing complexity of IC design. But the convenience offered by predefined digital CMOS standard cells has come at the price of overall chip-level efficiency. Standard-cell-based ICs are rarely optimized for their intended application, so ICs are not as small, fast or power-efficient as they could be. Nangate cell library creation and optimization tools provide the answer to this dilemma. Nangate tools enable custom tailoring of digital cell libraries to meet specific design targets. Libraries can be optimized for design goals such as power consumption, die area, operating frequency or required yield â€“ as opposed to being designed for a broad range of standard requirements. The result: improvements in IC performance can be achieved at much lower cost and with considerably less effort than using full-custom design methods.
Industry Groups: Consumer Electronics, Design, Hardware, Science and Engineering, Software
Founders: Jens C. Michelsen, Jens P. Tagore-Brage, Jesper Knudsen

Description: AudienceRun is an American ad network that helps publishers increase their digital advertising revenue.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: AudienceRun is an international ad network that started in 2010 in France. In 2018 the company expanded by moving its headquarters to the United States. AudienceRun is connected to the biggest international SSP platforms which allows it to serve publishers from all over the world. The company operates at an international level and is continually working on innovative ways to address the demand of both publishers and advertisers. Through the years, the AudienceRun experts have come to the conclusion that keeping web visitors engaged is crucial for the website’s monetization. This requires agility in ad formats but also understanding the needs of a constantly evolving environment. AudienceRun offers standard IAB formats. Those are the most commonly-used sizes and include: 728x90 - leaderboard/ 300x600 - half page ad/ 970x250 - billboard/  320x50 - mobile leaderboard. As these are the most common types of ads, inserting them on a website is an effective way to maximize display ad earnings. Most publishers adapt their website designs so that they could include these ad units and therefore not to miss an opportunity.  AudienceRun has developed UpNext format, a technology inspired by the Youtube "Up Next" model where videos are displayed next to or below the video a user is watching. They are automatically selected based on several factors, including what is currently being watched. AudienceRun UpNext format is an answer to the way people consume information online. It is a discrete cross device solution that respects the website’s interface and gives the right user experience. The format appears at the bottom right corner of the page when the user has read a certain amount of lines and wishes to continue navigating through rest of the website. Fixed Header and Fixed Footer are cross device ad formats that are placed, one at the top of the webpage and the other one at the bottom. They are always visible to users during their navigation. The advantage is that they do not interfere with reading experience and help publishers significantly increase their digital advertising revenue as the user do not feel the need to close them. 	 Interstitial Mobile ad is a full-screen ad format using creative mechanisms that targets the constantly increasing mobile audience. These type of ads have a high engagement rate as users cannot simply ignore the ad. They have to make a choice between the ad and continuing to the website.
Industry Groups: Advertising, Content and Publishing, Internet Services, Media and Entertainment, Sales and Marketing

Description: An Austin-based national nonprofit corporation that delivers a broad range of technical.
Headquarters Regions: Southern US
Full Description: Knowbility, Inc. is an Austin-based national nonprofit corporation that delivers a broad range of technical and consulting services to ensure that Internet and other technology products are accessible to people with disabilities, i.e. people who are blind, visually impaired, have mobility impairments, cognitive, learning or other disabilities and use assistive technology for computer access. Knowbility’s team of experts is internationally recognized for its role in helping to create the worldwide standard for web accessibility implementation and training. As a result, the company is a preeminent source for guidance in meeting government and international accessibility standards. Since its founding in 1999, Knowbility has worked with hundreds of community-based organizations, institutions of higher education, local and regional educational entities, government agencies and corporations throughout the nation. Knowbility has guided the creation of more than 1,000 accessible web sites, meeting the highest accessibility standards and has trained thousands of corporate and government agency personnel in best practices in accessibility.
Industry Groups: Education, Government and Military, Information Technology, Internet Services, Other, Professional Services, Social Impact

Description: Grace Matthews is recognized globally as a leader in M&A advisory services for manufacturers and distributors of specialty.
Headquarters Regions: Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: Grace Matthews, Inc. is recognized worldwide as a leader in transaction advisory services for manufacturers and distributors throughout the chemical and materials value chain.   Their practice is global in scope, and includes advising on sell-side transactions for private companies and private equity holdings, divestitures / carve-outs for large corporations; buy-side work, typically for large, public companies or major multi-nationals and sponsor-backed chemical platforms; leveraged transactions involving raising debt and/or equity capital, strategic advisory analysis, and transaction fairness opinions and valuations.   From a mergers and acquisitions perspective, no industry is more challenging than chemicals.  Since their  founding, they have encountered and resolved almost every transactional issue imaginable:  legacy superfund sites, contaminated groundwater and soil, open-ended TSCA exposure, carve outs of troubled assets, tax matters, family disputes, underfunded pensions, potential Foreign Corrupt Practices Act violations, minority shareholder litigation, and distressed or bankruptcy situations, among others.  Addressing these issues, and having the persistence to go on and complete a successful transaction, has become the heart of their  business.  What they have come to understand is that this hard-earned experience is a competitive advantage for Grace Matthews, and for their clients.  There is no shortcut to developing expertise.  You do it with bumps, bruises and a lot of shoe leather.  They always take a very detailed approach in understanding their  client, their business, and all the relevant circumstances that could impact a merger or acquisition, because they understand that minimizing risk is as important as maximizing value.
